The term “does not substantially bind” to a protein or cells, as used herein, means does not bind or does not bind with a high affinity to the protein or cells, i.e. binds to the protein or cells with a K<sub>D </sub>of 1.0×10<sup>−6 </sup>M or more, more preferably 1.0×10<sup>−5 </sup>M or more, more preferably 1.0×10<sup>−4 </sup>M or more, more preferably 1.0×10<sup>−3 </sup>M or more, even more preferably 1.0×10<sup>−2 </sup>M or more.
The term “high affinity” for an IgG antibody refers to an antibody having a K<sub>D </sub>of 1.0×10<sup>−7 </sup>M or less, more preferably 1.0×10<sup>−10 </sup>M or less, even more preferably 1.0×10<sup>−9 </sup>M or less, and even more preferably 1.0×10<sup>−10 </sup>M or less for a target antigen.
For example, “high affinity” binding for an isotype refers to an antibody having a K<sub>D </sub>of 10<sup>−6 </sup>M or less, inure preferably 10<sup>−7</sup>M or less, even more preferably 10<sup>−8 </sup>M or less.
